Abstract: ion in Process Planning Abstract Attempting to automate the entire process planning task tends to lead to systems of limited scope. Industry needs the benefits of generative computer aided process planning (CAPP) now however, so an approach to its introduction is needed that allows for both short-term benefits and long-term extendibility. This paper describes such an approach, based on raising the level of abstraction at which manual process planning is performed. By allowing planners to concentrate less on how things are done, and more on what is to be done, their workload could be reduced. Further, high level process plans have potential advantages over more detailed ones, and greater production efficiency could be obtained through allowing the precise manufacturing methods to be optimised computationally. This optimisation task is a complex one, but an appropriate technique is suggested. 
