Reference-contexts: 1. Introduction Process planning is the task of specifying how something is to be manufactured. A process plan is a list of operations which, if followed, will transform a given raw material into a finished part. Much has been said about the potential benefits of computer aided process planning (CAPP) <ref> (e.g. Chang 1990 p.5) </ref>. Although CAPP is being used successfully in industry, most of these systems are retrieval type (variant) systems. These systems require a human operator to input simplified data about the part to be manufactured, and to edit the standard plan retrieved for the specific situation in hand. <p> Present CAPP systems tend either to automate only a small part of the total process planning task, or deal with only a limited range of components <ref> (Chang 1990, p. viii) </ref>. An automatic CAPP system is therefore beyond the state of the art for most companies. Even if this were not so, the development and application of such a system could take many man-years.
